O. Keller‚¹ who has collected and used with much ingenuity all the available evidence on the subject, gives the palm of antiquity to the Scholia of Porphyrion. The only limit set to their date by external testimony is to be found in the mention of Porphyrion's name by Charisius, a grammatical writer, usually placed about A. D. 400 ς, but Keller thinks they are as early as 200-250 ΛΑ). The evidence on which he relies consists wholly of indications in the Scholia them- selves, such as (a) the writer's personal knowledge of Rome coupled Ὦ, with the fact that he never alludes to ‘the walls of Aurelian (mn. 27 1), ' v while he recognizes the older gates, as e. g. thea Porta Esquilina on ³ Epod. 5. 100, Sat. 1. 8. 1 ; (b) his use of Parthi, Parthicus, etc. as ἃ designations of the great eastern monarchy, in several places where the Pseudo-Acron uses Persae, Persicus, a natural variation if the fall of Parthia and the rise of the Persian dynasty of the Sassanidae (3.9. 226) had taken place between the two dates ; (c) his way of speaking of the religious ceremonies of heathen Rome as though they were still observed in his own time. Contrast, e. g. his note on Od. 3. 11. 6 ‘ fidicines hodieque Rornae sacrificiis adhiberi videmus' with Acron’s ‘ et in sacrificiis fidicines adhiberi consueverant,' or that on Od. 2. 16. 14 ‘ salinum, patella in qua primitiae dis cum sale dantur’ with Acron's ‘ patella in qua dis primitiae offerebantur,’ or lastly, that on 3. 5. 1 1 ‘ Aeternam Vestam, propter aeternos ignes qui in ara eius coluntur' with Acron's ‘ aeterni ignis qui in ara eius indefesse colebatur!

The genuine Acron wrote earlier than Porphyrion, if the latter’s d* quotation of him on Sat. 1. 8. 25 is not an interpolation, ‘memini me legere apud Helenium Acronem Saganam fuisse libertum Pom- ponii senatoris qui a triumviris est proscriptus.' It is to be remarked, however, that the statement thus quoted does not occur in the Scholia which go under Acron's name. On the other hand, we find in them, the change of tense already noticed with respect to sacrifices, etc„
